00:06:12.050 --> 00:06:15.217
Let me show you a plot of the voltage.

00:06:18.747 --> 00:06:19.715
Here's the voltage here.

00:06:19.715 --> 00:06:20.965
This is v of t.

00:06:21.905 --> 00:06:25.988
And that we decided was
equal to 10 cosine two t.

00:06:28.031 --> 00:06:31.107
Starts at a value of 10,
the time equals zero,

00:06:31.107 --> 00:06:33.601
and then forms a cosine
wave that goes up and down

00:06:33.601 --> 00:06:36.268
between plus and minus 10 volts.

00:06:37.569 --> 00:06:38.863
Now let me show you what it looks like

00:06:38.863 --> 00:06:41.763
when we plot both i and
v on the same graph,

00:06:41.763 --> 00:06:46.421
and we can see the timing
relationship between them.

00:06:46.421 --> 00:06:49.421
So this is a plot of i of t in blue,

00:06:52.345 --> 00:06:54.095
and v of t in orange.

00:06:57.331 --> 00:06:59.992
One them is a sine wave,
the current is a sine wave,

00:06:59.992 --> 00:07:02.409
and voltage is a cosine wave.

00:07:04.987 --> 00:07:06.817
So this is what we were going for.

00:07:06.817 --> 00:07:09.588
This is the natural
response of an LC circuit,

00:07:09.588 --> 00:07:12.028
and we had two specific
component values in it.

00:07:12.028 --> 00:07:14.819
We saw that we came out with
both current and voltage

00:07:14.819 --> 00:07:17.319
looking like sinusoidal waves.

00:07:18.724 --> 00:07:19.662
This LC circuit,

00:07:19.662 --> 00:07:22.189
this is where sine waves
come from in electronics.

00:07:22.189 --> 00:07:23.242
It's pretty cool.

